    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Out of the box GA tracks visited pages on it's load / refresh. So it has a hard time measure IS pages because there are no refreshes and page is re-rendered on each key stroke with JavaScript.\r\nGA (or any other analytics tool)  provides a way how to track those re-renders by sending pageViews programatically from JavaScript. But a lot of our customers struggle on how to plug it to IS, what queries and what data send to GA.\r\n\r\nAnd this is issue what this widget solves. It pushes only relevant queries and relevant data to GA and make it easy for our customers to integrate GA to their IS pages. So they can analyse searches in their GA dashboard, connect searches with their conversions, analyse how many users use search on their website, what are the conversion rates for each search query etc. \r\n\r\nDoes it make sense? :)\r\n\r\nAbout the timeout - we don't want to send each keystroke to GA to reduce the noise of data. So that's why there is a 3s (by default) timeout and the push to GA is made with latest rendered data when the search is probably finished. Is there a better way to do it?\r\n\r\n-------------------\r\n\r\nToday I got a great help from @bobylito and we refactored the widget a lot. And in the end it won't be `ga` widget but `analytics` widget and it'll support more analytics services then just GA. Currently proposed API is:\r\n\r\n```js\r\nsearch.addWidget(\r\n  instantsearch.widgets.analytics({\r\n    services: ['ga', 'segment.io', 'gtm'],\r\n    configuration = {\r\n      'ga': {...},\r\n      'segment.io': {...}\r\n    }\r\n  })\r\n);\r\n```\r\n\r\nI'd like to push it this afternoon.\r\n\r\nWDYT @vvo?",
